## Security baseline
- Treat all external input as untrusted.
- Validate and sanitize at system boundaries.
- Apply least privilege in design and runtime behavior.
- Never disable security checks to "make it work".

## Dependency management
- Use Go modules cleanly and intentionally.
- Keep go.mod and go.sum tidy and review dependency additions carefully.
- Prefer upgrading dependencies rather than pinning old vulnerable versions without cause.
- Avoid unnecessary indirect dependency bloat.

## Vulnerability management
- Run govulncheck regularly and in CI where practical.
- Treat reachable vulnerabilities as release-blocking unless explicitly risk-accepted.
- Reassess vulnerable transitive dependencies promptly.

## Crypto and transport
- Prefer standard library crypto and TLS unless a specialized library is clearly justified.
- Do not invent crypto.
- Use secure defaults and review transport-level assumptions carefully.

## Secrets
- Never commit secrets, credentials, API keys, tokens, or certificates.
- Load secrets from the environment or dedicated secret management systems.